history.content: CS 61A and EE 16A are great courses for your first semester. CS 70 can be hard for those without much proofs experience but, like everything else in life, it is a skill that just takes practice. If you're having second thoughts about 70 there are course notes/practice worksheets available online for you at https://www.eecs70.org/ to check out. That being said I think 70 is a great class and that would be a great learning experience for your first semester at Cal!

children.subject:
I took Math54 already in my community college. I don't want to take EE16B directly because I have no background in circuits , so I want to start with EE16A. 

You think its reasonable?

It's very reasonable, and in fact reccomended, to take EE16A before EE16B, especially if you have no circuits background. I had somewhat of a circuits background from highschool physics and selft studied the 16A material not covered in 54 before taking 16B and was able to do well in that class. I think this only worked because I had a basic understanding of current flow, electric potential, etc. Some of the linear algebra will be a repetition, but if you are truly new to circuits, not skipping 16A is probably your best bet. Going right into 16B not comfortable looking at basic circuits will make labs a lot more difficult.
Just wanted to put out there while CS 70 is a good choice (it's my favorite class so far after one year here), Math 54 is also an option. If you're L&S, it will satisfy EE16A. requirement as well

Just fyi, I was also on the waitlist for EE16A, and I was able to get into the class by enrolling into a lab/discussion section with open seats! Getting those are more important than being ahead on the waitlist, so just in case you wanted that option.
